# Editing discipline

Hard-won lessons. Apply them before showing Lisa any edit.

## 1. Look at the artifact before inferring

If a fact lives in a file you can open — a screenshot, a video, a component — open it. Do not reason in circles about something you can verify in seconds. Ground claims in evidence; infer only when there is nothing to look at.

- Example: which UI element came from which design is answered by reading `fb-before.png` and `msgr-before.png`, not by guessing.

## 2. Edit in full context, never line-by-line

Re-read the entire paragraph (or function) before AND after a change. A sentence that reads fine alone can break the passage — e.g. a forward reference to a term not yet introduced.

## 3. Don't ship regressions while polishing

Re-run the constraints already set before presenting: no em-dashes, Lisa's chosen punctuation, settled wording. "Improving" one thing must not reintroduce something already removed.

## 4. Accurate facts beat good prose

Wrong claims in polished copy are worse than plain accurate copy. Verify the claim is true (see #1) before refining its voice or rhythm.

## 5. Don't re-litigate settled decisions

Change the one thing asked. Leave everything already locked alone. Don't churn punctuation, wording, or layout the user has already approved.
